        <td bgcolor='black' valign=top width='100' nowrap><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'><b>Darkpakt</b></font></td>
        <td bgcolor='black' valign='top' width='100%'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> When EQ first came out it was really something else mainly because the graphics were cutting edge(immersion) and it had much more depth compared to regular FPS shooters.</P><P>But after sitting in one zone killing the same mobs for umpteen hours just to get a few levels, all the immersion and "purpose" of the game goes right out the window.  Instead of adventuring you're grinding.  Instead of enjoying the experience you're analyzing damage logs and finding the gaping holes in class balance.  After awhile even the NPCs aren't the enemy anymore, it's the puppet string holders in the corporate office that are the true enemy.</P><P>What I want to know is why you have to commit a lifetime to leveling up one character in a game with over a dozen classes?  Some classes are quite similar but IMO in most cases they each offer a very different journey and experience.  Even now it's much different to play a necromancer soloing in the crypts than it is to be a ranger hunting out in the forest.</P><P>Every MORPG that comes out seems to nerf exp gain down so much that you wind up reaching a point where you're bored to tears with it.  Why create so many different character classes if you're going to make the time committment so ridiculous?</P><P>I would much rather enjoy a rich and varied experience with a number of different characters instead walking into a zone for the 1000X time, punching the timeclock and standing on a treadmill for 5 hours.  Repeating the same action over and over and seeing little gain.</P><P>I hope one of these days a developer will come along that doesn't have PNP geeks in mind.  I really believe that there are alot of gamers out there who get tired of mindless repetition.  Who aren't so completely bored out of their minds or unfulfilled in their personal lives that they will stomach the redundancy of EQ's gameplay.</P><P> </font></td>
